narratives.question_text:
What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
(Your anonymous response to this question may be viewed by Yale College students, faculty, and advisers to aid in course selection and evaluating teaching.)
comments: Basic statistical knowledge and R, although I learned R from doing the psets, not the class.
I learned a ton, especially in the theoretical sense, about how to approach real life questions in order to obtain non-construed answers through multiple causal approaches.

Some data analysis techniques, I also learned how to push through crippling stress and depression because of the ridiculous curve in this class that was not modified for the COVID pandemic. SERIOUSLY UNREASONABLE compared to what other members of the economics department have done. The situation surrounding mental health at Yale has only gotten worse the longer we have been forced to isolate, AND THIS COURSE WAS UNWILLING TO ACCOMMODATE FOR THE DIFFICULTIES STUDENTS FACE.
I took this class for the economics major and didn't find the content super interesting, but I did learn skills that I could see being useful when analyzing economic data or doing research.

This course was a true introduction to econometrics and data analysis. We covered probability and statistical analysis techniques in the first half, and then we finished the semester we experimental techniques for analyzing data (Random Experiment, Diff-in-diff, Regression Discontinuity, and Instrumental Variables).
i definitely look at statistics more critically now.
I learned how to program in R.
econometrics
Critical higher-order reasoning skills, and quantitative skills

I learned many different ways to relate probabilities and apply them to the real world. I also learned the meaning of a linear regression, along with all of the components that must be factored in to appropriately regress something.

I learned about various econometrics concepts like randomized experiments, diff-in-diff, regression discontinuity, instrumental variables, hypothesis testing, p-values, sample vs population statistics, etc. I also learned some R basics.
Learned a lot about data analytics.

This course provided a broad introduction to basic statistics and its applications to the field of econometrics. After learning some basic statistics, you apply knowledge of linear regression to answer interesting questions related to everything from returns to education to womens fertility. You will also get a flavor for programming in R, though I wouldnt say it could even be considered a comprehensive introduction.
I learned basic statistic concepts and how to use R
Learned a lot about the history of the market as well as how to identify different trends
I learned about important statistical concepts, how to think about data, and the powerful statistical package of R. I also learned how these data analysis methods are used in real data studies
statistics
Learned the basics of probability and econometrics, and gained familiarity with R.
I learned about the foundations of data analysis specifically relating to economics. Basic R coding as well.
Insight into how to use stats and econ together
I learned how to apply statistics to economic concepts. I also learned how to use R.
I learned valuable econometrics skills such as regression discontinuity, differences-in-differences, and instrumental variables.
I developed a more analytical mindset fueled by many of the statistical theories we learned in class. I also learned a lot about how these theories applied to real life situations
Basic understanding of coding in R and statistics. This course basically teaches how to critically interpret data- which is either very useful or useful.

General skills in probability, statistics, and econometrics such as hypothesis testing, linear regression, and causation tests. An introduction to each of these concepts and just getting a fairly solid overview of what econometrics is like and how it's used in real-world research/situations.
Econometrics! And R.
other than the course material, I learned more about myself in regards to the better ways I learn, retain new material, and things that did not help me when studying.
Lots of stats, some review from high school. Learned R.
Knowledge of probability theory, basic statistics, and R.

-Probabilities (marginal and joint probability, conditionality, Bayes' rule)
-Statistics (variance, covariance,
-Probability distributions (probability functions, normalisation)
-Hypothesis testing and confidence intervals
-Linear regression
-Regression fit
Learned the basics of econometrics, which to me was a way of thinking about cause and effect and a curiosity about unobservable factors
I learned about the basics of econometrics and R Coding
I learned a ton about combining Economics with Data Science. This class very helpful in teaching me how to interact with Economics using statistical and data analysis techniques.

I learned a lot about statistics and probability. I also learned how to analyze data and isolate the useful information from data sets, as well as perform regressions and understand the results of regressions.
Having no prior coding or stats experience I learned a lot about both in this class

narratives.question_text:
What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
(Your anonymous response to this question may be viewed by Yale College students, faculty, and advisers to aid in course selection and evaluating teaching.)
comments:
Strengths: you learn a lot and some very useful things, the lectures are interesting sometimes, especially when applying what we learn in class to the real world.
Weaknesses: the psets cover a lot of things we do not learn in class, and there are very few resources to get help on them.

Weaknesses: Prof. Ryan is a smart guy, but he's not a great professor. Lecture pace needs to be sped up in first 2/3 of course, slowed down significantly in last 1/3. Midterm was way too long and difficult, almost twice the size of previous midterms...

Strengths: Strong TF support, good peer tutors. Would 11/10 go to them during office hours for help. material is also very interesting

The strength lies in the building of the foundation from probability all the way to IV. A weakness was the ambiguous role that R played within the class. It is necessary but I'm not sure to what extent it helped me understand anything or apply it in r studio.
Strengths: Although virtual, Professor Ryan did a great job of keeping the lecture interactive.

Strengths: forces kids to learn because it is required by the economics major and imposes a ridiculous curve
Weaknesses: forces kids to learn because it is required by the economics major and imposes a ridiculous curve

The professor and teaching team were well-organized and I felt that they knew what they were doing. I think some of the problem sets were a bit too long and unrealistic for students (who are taking 3 or 4 other classes) to reasonably complete. Besides that, I felt it was a well structured course.

The course was good overall, but sometimes the information taught in lecture was hard to apply to the questions asked in problem sets. A little more guidance on how to apply the information taught would've been more helpful. It was also difficult to do the PSETs when some material needed to answer questions wasn't taught until the class right before the PSET was due.

strengths - outside resources (pt, office hours) 
weaknesses - lecture was just... dull

This was a poorly taught course. I fortunately took statistics in high school. Professor Ryan overcomplicates simple concepts

Also, worst exam design I have ever seen. No one has time to read paragraphs on paragraphs in the middle of exams--include just the relevant information. Time constraint on exam is ridiculous--tests on test taking speed and not class concepts.

Strengths: Much of the course material related to real-world applications is very interesting. It brings up real problems in economics, development economics, and public policy. The problem sets are also quite interesting in this regard.

Weaknesses: The non-real-world material is very dry. It's obviously useful, but that doesn't change it.

Strengths: I think professor Ryan did a great job at organizing the lectures and teaching the material
Weaknesses: a lot of material in a short amount of time
Exams were difficult, although the content was taught well.

I thought that overall, the course was outstanding. The strengths include all of the TFs and Professors. I believe that the content was very deep, and I think that they did an outstanding job explaining it at the introductory level.

Strengths: Prof Ryan is a great lecturer, the TAs were great, the material was relevant
Weaknesses: While Prof Ryan tried to tie all his examples to the real-world, sometimes the examples were hard to understand. For example, when the examples would involve finance, I had a hard time wrapping my head around them rather than focusing on the underlying econometrics principles Prof Ryan was trying to teach us. Would be great if these examples could be further simplified. It would have also been nice if psets and quizzes were due on a specific day of the week. It would be easier to plan out our weeks, especially because we have other assignments due too in other courses.
Course is fast paced but well taught

The TFs for the course were excellent. Jaime, the head TF, organized the course extremely well. I always felt like I had the resources and practice materials necessary to succeed. Nevertheless, the lectures were often quite dry. You are taking this course for the Econ major, so you likely cant avoid it.

The statistics concepts were not taught in an intuitive way. The lectures were more confusing than helpful. Section helped clear a lot of things up. The midterm was also far too long for the time allotted and much harder than previous years.
Lectures could be more intersecting and engaging
More help on coding in R they helped for the first 2 psets but then we started everything on scratch
Learning how to use the code should be emphasized more

This course was very interesting and one strength was that it used lots of case studies to emphasize the real-world importance of the seemingly conceptual material. The course could be improved in that the material needed for the problem sets could be made more explicit in lecture, but that's not a big issue because there is so much to cover and everything students need has been covered.
I don't understand in what way this course wasn't just stats 101 (I've never taken stats) --- I thought it was a bit rushed in some areas --- don't think anything in R was that helpful

The content during the lectures and the content expected to be known on the problem sets often feel worlds apart. I feel if there was more emphasis on the actual number crunching itself, instead of a flurry of tangentially related real life examples, I would've developed a better level of econometric calculation ability.
I cried a lot, but it pushed me to do things I never though I would do, like learning a coding language.
Strengths were the TAs; they were very helpful. Weaknesses were the professor; I feel like he did not explain the concepts in class as well as he could have.
Clear and easy to follow. Can get a little dry at times

I really enjoyed the lectures and thought that they were very comprehensive. I also found the office hours to be very helpful and sections to be very organized. The only thing is that I felt that the lectures moved a bit quickly, so I would have appreciated if they had slowed down a bit.

I feel like there were times when we get too bogged down in the math behind the statistics and there were also other times I wish we got more mathematical background. However, the course was a very strong course in teaching the material in a comprehensive way

Despite the course material being applicable to virtually every aspect of Economics, the lectures in this course are very boring. I think it is because the concepts are hard to understand, (i.e., the difference in difference in a regression) making the first time through a new concept a slog. I think this course could be improved by providing pre-reading or videos prior to class, so when running through a paper which used a concept, students can actually know what is happening and not just be struggling to learn the differences between similar words.

I feel like there were a number of things required for problem sets/exams that could have been taught more explicitly during lecture. One of the components of the course is to learn R for econometrics, but there were many R concepts required in the problem sets that I don't think were taught particularly well in the lectures and made things confusing. Otherwise, I thought the course was a solid overview of econometrics concepts as a whole that should be useful for anyone who wants to go into this type of field.
I think the course was taught well and at a good pace. The lectures and the psets couldve been more connected.
strength: especially during a time like this, I felt it was crucial to make the lecture slides easy to read and easy to read through.

Strengths
-Professor Ryan is an excellent lecturer, and his lecture slides are perfectly structured for both the lecture itself and for doing content review afterwards
-The TAs are the best- hats off to them. The piazza page is very well administered with prompt and helpful responses to questions. 
-The TAs create invaluable section recap slides that are short summaries of that week's content
-The lectures and psets do an excellent job connecting statistical concepts to the work being done by economists, and real-world issues
-Psets are very well designed, helping to internalise the course material. 

Weaknesses
-While the quizzes are a good way to recap content, I don't think they are as low-stakes as intended.  I spent far, far more time working on psets than quizzes, but each pset was not weighted that much more heavily (5% of total grade per pset vs 3.33% per quiz). I recommend that the course either reduce the weightage of quizzes, or increase their number.

Potential weaknesses are the timing on the exams. The midterm in particular left most students without time to finish. HOWEVER, the final was much better paced, so it's likely the instructors already implemented this feedback.
This class was very well explained but could slow down at times.
This class was very good, fruitful, and well-structured.

The strengths of the course are the lecture slides - the definitions of the terms and the explanations of those were clear.
Also, the discussion sections were very helpful to understand the material from the week. 

The weaknesses are that the examples in class, done through polls, were not explained very clearly and were hard to follow at times. Also, the midterm exam was unexpectedly difficult (relative to the practice/past midterm exams). It would be very helpful if the lectures were slowed down a bit to allow for students to fully digest the material. Also, even though the problem sets were assigned two weeks before they are due, the lecture material needed to complete the problem sets was only provided one or two lectures before the due date (approximately 1-3 days), resulting in a stressful time to complete the PSETs.

I have numerous complaints about this class. First of all, I do no believe that people coming into this class with no coding or stats experience have a fair experience. It is expected that I would struggle more with problem sets and would face an initial learning curve to coding having no background. However, it is extremely hard to compete for good grades if a substantial percentage of the class has already seen this material before and practised solving similar problems in the past. Furthermore, there were not enough office hours every week, especially when compared to other classes at Yale. This is especially true in the finals period were in intermediate macroeconomics there were numerous pages of office hours links for the finals week, with multiple hours every single day, whereas for econ 117 there was about one hour worth of office hours every day in the final week leading up to the exam. I thought this was unacceptable.

strength: office hours and section (jaime)
weakness: strict curve and hard exams

narratives.question_text: Among the practices in this course geared toward learning during the COVID-19 pandemic, which succeeded and which could be improved? Please comment on course practices that allowed for virtual engagement. (Your anonymous response to this question may be viewed by Yale College students, faculty, and advisers to aid in course selection and evaluating teaching.)
comments: All courses should be virtual. class in person is wasted, especially not at 2x speed
The polling system seemed to be a very effective way to gauge our collective understanding while class was still live.

I'd say the only thing that succeeded transitioning to the pandemic was the organization of the class slides. Otherwise, as I mentioned before, the accommodations of this course were SERIOUSLY UNREASONABLE compared to what other members of the economics department have done. The situation surrounding mental health at Yale has only gotten worse the longer we have been forced to isolate, AND THIS COURSE WAS UNWILLING TO ACCOMMODATE FOR THE DIFFICULTIES STUDENTS FACE.
Live virtual lectures were engaging through the use of Zoom polls. It made the class more interactive.
Success: lectures
The content seemed pretty dry, I wish there were in-person workshops.
N/A
Section was helpful, but lectures on zoom were difficult to engage in sometimes.
I enjoyed having lectures to reference back to. The synchronous sections also helped reinforce concepts.
They couldve had review sessions for the final and midterm - nothing like that was offered
Slowing down on the material
eh
Helpful slides
I thought that the lectures, sections, and office hours were well done for the COVID format.
As previously indicated, I think that the "final" versions of lecture slides should have been improved. The poll questions were helpful!
I think the polls were really great although there may be better ways to fill the 1-2 minutes of silence that accompanied each one
Virtual lectures are terrible- the green screen helped.
Section was very helpful. The polls were also great because I could also see how other students understood the material.
I feel Professor Ryan did a great job given these circumstances.

The poll questions asked in lecture were a good way for me to check if I actually understood the material. Many of the poll questions were challenging and forced me to actually think or jot down calculations. But thankfully, the professor would always walk through the question afterwards, which was helpful for when I didn't understand what to do.
This course didn't really suffer for being virtual. Good stuff all around.
The lectures were a little fast but section helped explain them more
I thought this class was carried very well, considering it was even during the pandemic.

The Piazza site was helpful, as it allowed for students to get their questions answered when they couldn't attend office hours. 
On the other hand, the polls felt rushed and were not fully explained at times.

narratives.question_text:
Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
(Your anonymous response to this question may be viewed by Yale College students, faculty, and advisers to aid in course selection and evaluating teaching.)
comments: This class pushed me out of the CS+econ joint major. You have to take it if you're considering a major that requires the class, though. If you don't already know R, you'll need to learn that because they will not teach you it, so get comfortable with Google and asking your friends for help (I once tweeted asking for how to do something in R, so really just use all your resources).
well i mean you have to take it right?
Yes, if you hope to do statistical analysis or research in Econ.

Econ Major: Yes
If not: No
NO, BUT THEY WILL BE FORCED TO TAKE IT BECAUSE IT IS REQUIRED BY THE MAJOR

I would not recommend this class to another student unless they have to take it for their major. As someone who did it to fulfill a major requirement, it wasn't too painful but I would not have taken the class otherwise.
Yes, it is a great introduction course to statistical data analysis, especially if you have no experience and would also like to learn how to code in R.
Yes, econometrics is a useful and practical course for any Econ-related major.
i feel like if you're here this is the means to an end. it's definitely doable but prepare to do a lot of extra work if you're not a big math person just to get by
No. Only do this if you have to for the Economics major. Otherwise, why???????
No. While it can be useful, it's probably a better idea to take a stats course and do Econ applications of the material with a peer tutor or your friends.
Yes, if they need to take econ 117
Definitely should take it if you want to learn econometrics, or as part of the major. Otherwise, tend to avoid it.
Yes, as long as you know what you are getting into. I think that this course would be valuable for anyone in any major.
Yes, it is a good course.
Yes, you have to take it to be an economics major.
I would recommend it if you want a broad introduction to econometrics, but if you really want to pursue any sort of empirical research, you will likely need to take additional classes.
Dont take it if you dont have to - there are better stats classes out there
Yes

Yes, if you are interested in seeing how economics is really done in the world outside of the lecture hall - then this course will really interest you. Conceptually, it may be a bit of a challenge at certain points because of the many definitions and not exactly seeing how they all fit together, but if you stick with it everything will make sense!
On it's own no. I don't think this should be a required Econ course. If it is part of more statistics classes and you want to pursue statistics, maybe --- but I don't know
You are most likely taking this course as a requirement for the economics major, my recommendation is that you take it as early as you can so it doesn't burden you later on in your Yale career.
Its good if you want to apply data analysis to economics. Otherwise, just taking a class in S&DS would be better.
Yes, if they plan to go into economics I think that it was very practical.

I would only take this course if you have previously taken a stats course at Yale or AP stats in high school. It puts you at a great advantage over many of your peers, but it's not impossible to do well without that background. I'd also only take this course if I were for sure majoring in Economics.
If you are even somewhat interested in statistics and aren't too scared of math, it's definitely a fantastic course that you will learn a lot from
Yes- you need this course to understand anything about the real world. It is not thrilling (lest tabulated data is your jam) but it is necessary and helpful.

I think this course will probably be difficult to enjoy unless you already know that you want to do something related to econometrics. Many of the concepts can be somewhat stale at times and probably wouldn't be too interesting for people not interested in economics and statistics. But otherwise, it is a solid course that's required for most economics students anyways.
Yes I learned a lot.

This class will be difficult if you do not have any experience with probability and statistics. If you have taken a stats class before, it won't be so bad, but the class still moves pretty quickly. Overall, I would only recommend this class for someone who needs to take it for major requirements. Otherwise, just take an intro stats class.
Absolutely. Even if you're not majoring in econ, this is a great course to learn statistical thinking and get an insight into the kind of work that social scientists do.
Yes, would recommend. Even outside the econ major, it's a good intro to stats and to using R
Yes it is a hard but necessary class to understand analytics and coding
Yes, this is the course that made me realize how much I enjoyed Economics and S&DS.

If this course is not needed for your major, I would not recommend this course. The R coding part of the class is rushed and most of the class is revolved around theory, probability, statistics. That being said, if you want to learn the fundamentals of probability and statistics in a rigorous setting, this course achieves that.

Absolutely not. I think the material was important and I learned a lot but it was a significant struggle due to the bad organisation, bad delivery of material to accommodate students with no background and difficulty to compete with more experienced students.

no - not unless needed for major or you already know stats or r: if not its too difficult and the students who know more before entering course will block you from receiving a good grade bc of the strict curve
